# .env setup — note for judges

This project loads its configuration from a `.env` file in `person-a/`.
The `.env` itself is **not committed** (it contains secrets). A safe template
is checked in as [`person-a/.env.example`](person-a/.env.example).

## What you need to do

1. Copy the template:

   ```powershell
   cd person-a
   Copy-Item .env.example .env
   ```

   (or `cp .env.example .env` on macOS / Linux)

2. Open `person-a/.env` and set:

   ```
   LLM_PROVIDER=openai
   OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...your key here...
   OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-5.2
   ```

   This is the configuration we developed and tested against. Any
   modern OpenAI chat model will work (`gpt-5.2`, `gpt-5`, `gpt-4o`,
   `gpt-4o-mini`, …); we recommend `gpt-5.2` for the best plan quality.

3. Leave the other provider blocks (`GROQ_*`, `GEMINI_*`) empty unless
   you want to switch providers — the code supports Groq and Gemini as
   alternatives, plus an offline `stub` mode (`STUB_LLM=1`) that runs
   the full pipeline without any API calls if you just want to verify
   the architecture.

4. Then:

   ```powershell
   cd person-a
   npm install
   npm run eval     # runs the 4 sample hypotheses end-to-end
   npm start        # boots the SSE server on http://localhost:8787
   ```

## Why we ship `.env.example` and not `.env`

`.env` files routinely contain live API keys; committing them is a
standard OWASP-flagged mistake. The template documents every variable
the app reads, with safe defaults, so you can stand up your own copy
in under a minute.
